<?xml version="1.0" encoding="utf-8" standalone="yes"?><rss version="2.0" xmlns:atom="http://www.w3.org/2005/Atom"><channel><title>Twitter on Tim Hopper</title><link>https://tdhopper.com/tags/twitter/</link><description>Recent content in Twitter on Tim Hopper</description><generator>Hugo -- gohugo.io</generator><language>en-us</language><lastBuildDate>Thu, 17 Oct 2024 12:00:16 -0400</lastBuildDate><atom:link href="https://tdhopper.com/tags/twitter/index.xml" rel="self" type="application/rss+xml"/><item><title>Your Old Tweets from This Day</title><link>https://tdhopper.com/blog/your-old-tweets-from-this-day/</link><pubDate>Tue, 24 Jan 2017 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://tdhopper.com/blog/your-old-tweets-from-this-day/</guid><description>&lt;p>A while ago, I &lt;a class="link" href="https://gist.github.com/tdhopper/fccc4ab00a07cb290f1812d8ac5cc5f3" target="_blank" rel="noopener"
>published a Bash script&lt;/a> that will open a Twitter search page to show your old tweets from this day of the year. I have enjoyed using it to &lt;a class="link" href="https://twitter.com/tdhopper/status/559005293808746497" target="_blank" rel="noopener"
>see&lt;/a> &lt;a class="link" href="https://twitter.com/tdhopper/status/426718234461872130" target="_blank" rel="noopener"
>what&lt;/a> I was &lt;a class="link" href="https://twitter.com/tdhopper/status/691088342499381250" target="_blank" rel="noopener"
>thinking&lt;/a> &lt;a class="link" href="https://twitter.com/tdhopper/status/426702495361269760" target="_blank" rel="noopener"
>about&lt;/a> in &lt;a class="link" href="https://twitter.com/tdhopper/status/294300532770738176" target="_blank" rel="noopener"
>days&lt;/a> &lt;a class="link" href="https://twitter.com/tdhopper/status/29641415810088961" target="_blank" rel="noopener"
>gone&lt;/a> by.&lt;/p>
&lt;p>So I turned this into a Twitter account.&lt;/p>
&lt;blockquote class="twitter-tweet" data-lang="en">&lt;p lang="en" dir="ltr">Follow me to have a link tweeted @ you each day that will show your old tweets from that day of the year. &lt;a href="https://twitter.com/hashtag/experimental?src=hash">#experimental&lt;/a>&lt;/p>&amp;mdash; On This Day (@your_old_tweets) &lt;a href="https://twitter.com/your_old_tweets/status/819196698044014592">January 11, 2017&lt;/a>&lt;/blockquote>
&lt;script async src="//platform.twitter.com/widgets.js" charset="utf-8">&lt;/script>
&lt;p>If you follow &lt;a class="link" href="https://twitter.com/your_old_tweets" target="_blank" rel="noopener"
>@your_old_tweets&lt;/a>, it&amp;rsquo;ll tweet a link at you each day that will show you your old tweets from the day. It attempts to send it in the morning (assuming you have your &lt;a class="link" href="https://twitter.com/settings/account" target="_blank" rel="noopener"
>timezone set&lt;/a>).&lt;/p>
&lt;p>This runs on Amazon Lambda. The code is &lt;a class="link" href="https://github.com/tdhopper/your_old_tweets" target="_blank" rel="noopener"
>here&lt;/a>.&lt;/p></description></item><item><title>Stanford Encyclopedia of Philosophy Bot</title><link>https://tdhopper.com/blog/tweet-your-moon/</link><pubDate>Sun, 28 Feb 2016 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate><guid>https://tdhopper.com/blog/tweet-your-moon/</guid><description>&lt;p>I enjoy the &lt;a class="link" href="" >Stanford Encyclopedia of Philosophy&lt;/a>, so I created a &lt;a class="link" href="" >Twitter account&lt;/a> that tweets links to random articles from it.&lt;/p></description></item></channel></rss>